# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dpdk-networking
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] The **Data Plane Development Kit** (**DPDK**) is an open source software project managed by the Linux Foundation.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] It provides a set of data plane libraries and network interface controller polling-mode drivers for offloading TCP packet processing from the operating system kernel to processes running in user space.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] This offloading achieves higher computing efficiency and higher packet throughput than is possible using the interrupt-driven processing provided in the kernel.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] DPDK provides a programming framework for x86, ARM, and PowerPC processors and enables faster development of high speed data packet networking applications.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] It scales from mobile processors, such as Intel Atom, to server-grade processors, such as Intel Xeon.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] It supports instruction set architectures such as Intel, IBM POWER8, EZchip, and ARM.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] It is provided and supported under the open-source BSD license.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] DPDK was created by Intel engineer Venky Venkatesan, who is affectionately known as "The Father of DPDK." He died in 2018 after a long battle with cancer.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] The DPDK framework creates a set of libraries for specific hardware/software environments through the creation of an Environment Abstraction Layer (EAL).
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] The EAL hides the environment specifics and provides a standard programming interface to libraries, available hardware accelerators and other hardware and operating system (Linux, FreeBSD) elements.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] Once the EAL is created for a specific environment, developers link to the library to create their applications.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] For instance, EAL provides the frameworks to support Linux, FreeBSD, Intel IA-32 or 64-bit, IBM POWER9 and ARM 32- or 64-bit.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] The EAL also provides additional services including time references, generic bus access, trace and debug functions and alarm operations.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] Using DPDK libraries one can implement a low overhead run-to-completion, pipeline or staged, event driven, or hybrid model completely in userspace eliminating kernel and kernel to user copy.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] Hardware assists from NIC/Regex/Accelerators, libraries enhanced to make use of Intelligence Storage Acceleration (ISA) for bulk performance and accessing devices via polling helps to eliminate the performance overhead of interrupt too.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] Hugepages are used for large memory pool allocation, to decrease the amount of lookups and page management.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] The DPDK also includes software examples that highlight best practices for software architecture, tips for data structure design and storage, application profiling and performance tuning utilities and tips that address common network performance deficits.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] The DPDK includes drivers for many hardware types.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] There have been some additional out-of-tree plugin drivers in the past, which are now considered deprecated.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] The DPDK was originally designed to run using a bare-metal mode which is currently deprecated.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] DPDK's EAL provides support for Linux or FreeBSD userland application.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] EAL can be extended in order to support any processors.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] DPDK is now an open-source project under the Linux Foundation, supported by many companies.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] The technical activities are overseen by a Technical Board.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] Beside Intel, which is a contributor to the DPDK, several other vendors also support the DPDK within their products and some offer additional training, support and professional services.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] The list of vendors who have announced DPDK support includes: 6WIND, ALTEN Calsoft Labs, Advantech, Brocade, Big Switch Networks, Mellanox Technologies, Radisys, Tieto, Wind River, Lanner Inc. and NXP.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] This is 'line rate' on a 10 Gbps interface.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] Open vSwitch (OVS) has a limited set of features running userland that can be leveraged to bypass the Linux kernel OVS processing.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] This use case of OVS with DPDK userland is usually named OVS-DPDK.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] It is mostly deployed with OpenStack Neutron but it assumes that many features and software-defined networking (SDN) capabilities of Openstack are disabled.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] For instance, when OVS-DPDK is used, Neutron provides a lower level of security than when OVS kernel is used (no stateful firewalling, less security group).
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] The FD.IO VPP platform is an extensible framework that provides out-of-the-box production quality switch/router functionality.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] It is the open source version of Cisco's Vector Packet Processing (VPP) technology: a high performance, packet-processing stack that can run on commodity CPUs, and can leverage the Poll Mode Drivers for both NICs and cryptographic acceleration hardware and libraries.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] TRex is an open source traffic generator using DPDK.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] It generates L4–7 traffic based on pre-processing and smart replay of real traffic templates.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] TRex amplifies both client and server side traffic and can scale to 200 Gbit/s with one UCS using Intel XL710.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] TRex also supports multiple streams, ability to change any packet field and provides per stream statistics, latency and jitter.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] DTS (DPDK Test Suite) is a Python-based framework for functional tests and benchmarks.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] It is an open-source project, started in 2014, and is hosted on dpdk.org.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] It supports both software traffic generators like Scapy and dpdk-pktgen, and a hardware traffic generator like Ixia.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] DDP (Dynamic Device Personalization) is one of the new advanced features implemented with DPDK.
[src:dpdk-networking/data-plane-development-kit] It allows you to load firmware for a device dynamically, without resetting the host.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] There are many different ways to measure the performance of a network, as each network is different in nature and design.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] Performance can also be modeled and simulated instead of measured; one example of this is using state transition diagrams to model queuing performance or to use a Network Simulator.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] The available channel bandwidth and achievable signal-to-noise ratio determine the maximum possible throughput.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] It is not generally possible to send more data than dictated by the Shannon-Hartley Theorem.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] The *Time Window* is the period over which the throughput is measured.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] The choice of an appropriate time window will often dominate calculations of throughput, and whether latency is taken into account or not will determine whether the latency affects the throughput or not.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] The speed of light imposes a minimum propagation time on all electromagnetic signals.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] where s is the distance and cm is the speed of light in the medium (roughly 200,000 km/s for most fiber or electrical media, depending on their velocity factor).
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] This approximately means an additional millisecond round-trip delay (RTT) per 100 km (or 62 miles) of distance between hosts.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] Other delays also occur in intermediate nodes.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] In packet switched networks delays can occur due to queueing.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] In digital transmission, the number of **bit errors** is the number of received bits of a data stream over a communication channel that have been altered due to noise, interference, distortion or bit synchronization errors.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] The **bit error rate** or **bit error ratio** (**BER**) is the number of bit errors divided by the total number of transferred bits during a studied time interval.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] BER is a unitless performance measure, often expressed as a percentage.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] The **bit error probability** *pe* is the expectation value of the BER.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] The BER can be considered as an approximate estimate of the bit error probability.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] This estimate is accurate for a long time interval and a high number of bit errors.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] All of the factors above, coupled with user requirements and user perceptions, play a role in determining the perceived 'fastness' or utility, of a network connection.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] The relationship between throughput, latency, and user experience is most aptly understood in the context of a shared network medium, and as a scheduling problem.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] For some systems, latency and throughput are coupled entities.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] In TCP/IP, latency can also directly affect throughput.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] In TCP connections, the large bandwidth-delay product of high latency connections, combined with relatively small TCP window sizes on many devices, effectively causes the throughput of a high latency connection to drop sharply with latency.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] This can be remedied with various techniques, such as increasing the TCP congestion window size, or more drastic solutions, such as packet coalescing, TCP acceleration, and forward error correction, all of which are commonly used for high latency satellite links.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] TCP acceleration converts the TCP packets into a stream that is similar to UDP.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] Because of this, the TCP acceleration software must provide its own mechanisms to ensure the reliability of the link, taking the latency and bandwidth of the link into account, and both ends of the high latency link must support the method used.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] In the Media Access Control (MAC) layer, performance issues such as throughput and end-to-end delay are also addressed.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] Many systems can be characterized as dominated either by throughput limitations or by latency limitations in terms of end-user utility or experience.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] In some cases, hard limits such as the speed of light present unique problems to such systems and nothing can be done to correct this.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] Other systems allow for significant balancing and optimization for best user experience.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] A telecom satellite in geosynchronous orbit imposes a path length of at least 71000 km between transmitter and receiver. which means a minimum delay between message request and message receipt, or latency of 473 ms.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] This delay can be very noticeable and affects satellite phone service regardless of available throughput capacity.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] These long path length considerations are exacerbated when communicating with space probes and other long-range targets beyond Earth's atmosphere.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] The Deep Space Network implemented by NASA is one such system that must cope with these problems.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] Largely latency driven, the GAO has criticized the current architecture.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] Several different methods have been proposed to handle the intermittent connectivity and long delays between packets, such as delay-tolerant networking.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] At interstellar distances, the difficulties in designing radio systems that can achieve any throughput at all are massive.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] In these cases, maintaining communication is a bigger issue than how long that communication takes.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-performance] Transportation is concerned almost entirely with throughput, which is why physical deliveries of backup tape archives are still largely done by vehicle.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-processor] A **network processor** is an integrated circuit which has a feature set specifically targeted at the networking application domain.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-processor] Network processors are typically software programmable devices and would have generic characteristics similar to general purpose central processing units that are commonly used in many different types of equipment and products.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-processor] The processing of these packets has resulted in the creation of integrated circuits (IC) that are optimised to deal with this form of packet data.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-processor] Network processors have specific features or architectures that are provided to enhance and optimise packet processing within these networks.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-processor] Network processors have evolved into ICs with specific functions.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-processor] This evolution has resulted in more complex and more flexible ICs being created.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-processor] The newer circuits are programmable and thus allow a single hardware IC design to undertake a number of different functions, where the appropriate software is installed.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-processor] Reconfigurable Match-Tables were introduced in 2013 to allow switches to operate at high speeds while maintaining flexibility with respect to which network protocols are enabled on the device and/or how those protocols are processed.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-processor] The company Barefoot Networks was based around these processors and was later purchased by Intel in 2019.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-processor] An RMT pipeline relies on three main stages; the programmable parser, the Match-Action tables and the programmable deparser.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-processor] The parser reads the packet in chunks and processes these chunks to find out which protocols are used in the packet (Ethernet, VLAN, IPv4...) and extracts certain fields from the packet into the Packet Header Vector (PHV).
[src:dpdk-networking/network-processor] Certain fields in the PHV may be reserved for special uses such as present headers or total packet length.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-processor] The protocols are typically programmable, and so are the fields to extract.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-processor] The Match-Action tables are a series of units that read an input PHV and match certain fields in it using a crossbar and CAM memory.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-processor] The result is a wide instruction that operates on one or more fields of the PHV and data to support this instruction.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-processor] The output PHV is then sent to the next MA stage or to the deparser.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-processor] The deparser takes in the PHV as well as the original packet and its metadata (to fill in missing bits that weren't extracted into the PHV) and then outputs the modified packet as chunks.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-processor] The deparser, like the parser, is typically programmable and the two may share some configuration files.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-processor] FlexNIC attempts to apply this model to Network Interface Controllers allowing servers to send and receive packets at high speeds while maintaining protocol flexibility and without increasing the CPU overhead.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-processor] Modern network processors are also equipped with low-latency high-throughput on-chip interconnection networks optimized for the exchange of small messages among cores (few data words).
[src:dpdk-networking/network-processor] Such networks can be used as an alternative facility for the efficient inter-core communication aside of the standard use of shared memory.
[src:dpdk-networking/network-processor] Using the generic function of the network processor, a software program implements an application that the network processor executes, resulting in the piece of physical equipment performing a task or providing a service.
[src:dpdk-networking/output-virtualization] In virtualization, **single root input/output virtualization** (**SR-IOV**) is a specification that allows the isolation of PCI Express resources for manageability and performance reasons.
[src:dpdk-networking/output-virtualization] A single physical PCI Express bus can be shared in a virtual environment using the SR-IOV specification.
[src:dpdk-networking/output-virtualization] The SR-IOV offers different virtual functions to different virtual components (e.g. network adapter) on a physical server machine.
[src:dpdk-networking/output-virtualization] SR-IOV uses physical and virtual functions to control or configure PCIe devices.
[src:dpdk-networking/output-virtualization] Physical functions have the ability to move data in and out of the device while virtual functions are lightweight PCIe functions that support data flowing but also have a restricted set of configuration resources.
[src:dpdk-networking/output-virtualization] The virtual or physical functions available to the hypervisor or guest operating system depend on the PCIe device.
[src:dpdk-networking/output-virtualization] The SR-IOV allows different virtual machines (VMs) in a virtual environment to share a single PCI Express hardware interface.
[src:dpdk-networking/output-virtualization] In contrast, MR-IOV allows I/O PCI Express to share resources among different VMs on different physical machines.
[src:dpdk-networking/output-virtualization] A major field of application for SR-IOV is within high-performance computing (HPC).
[src:dpdk-networking/output-virtualization] The use of high-performance InfiniBand networking cards is growing within the HPC sector, and there is early research into the use of SR-IOV to allow for the use of InfiniBand within virtual machines such as Xen.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] In telecommunications, **packet switching** is a method of grouping data into short messages in fixed format, i.e., *packets,* that are transmitted over a telecommunications network.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Packets consist of a header and a payload.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] The header directs the packet to its destination, where the payload is extracted and used by an operating system, application software, or higher-layer protocols.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Packet switching is the primary basis for data communications in computer networks worldwide.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] During the early 1960s, American engineer Paul Baran developed a concept he called *distributed adaptive message block switching* as part of a research program at the RAND Corporation, funded by the United States Department of Defense.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] His proposal was to provide a fault-tolerant, efficient method for communication of voice messages using low-cost hardware to route the message blocks across a distributed network.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] His ideas contradicted then-established principles of pre-allocation of network bandwidth, exemplified by the development of telecommunications in the Bell System.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] The new concept found little resonance among network implementers until the independent work of British computer scientist Donald Davies at the National Physical Laboratory beginning in 1965.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Davies developed the concept for data communication using software switches in a high-speed computer network and coined the term *packet switching*.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] His work inspired numerous packet switching networks in the decade following, including the incorporation of the concept into the design of the ARPANET in the United States and the CYCLADES network in France.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] The ARPANET and CYCLADES were the primary precursor networks of the modern Internet.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Packet switching allows delivery of variable bit rate data streams, realized as sequences of short messages in fixed format, i.e.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] *packets*, over a computer network which allocates transmission resources as needed using statistical multiplexing or dynamic bandwidth allocation techniques.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] As they traverse networking hardware, such as switches and routers, packets are received, buffered, queued, and retransmitted (stored and forwarded), resulting in variable latency and throughput depending on link capacity and traffic load on the network.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Packet-based communication may be implemented with or without intermediate forwarding nodes (switches and routers).
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] In case of a shared physical medium (such as radio or 10BASE5), the packets may be delivered according to a multiple access scheme.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Packet switching contrasts with another principal networking paradigm, circuit switching, a method which pre-allocates dedicated network bandwidth specifically for each communication session, each having a constant bit rate and latency between nodes.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] A packet switch has four components: input ports, output ports, routing processor, and switching fabric.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] The concept of switching small blocks of data was invented independently by Paul Baran at the RAND Corporation during the early 1960s in the US and Donald Davies at the National Physical Laboratory (NPL) in the UK in 1965.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] In the late 1950s, the US Air Force established a wide area network for the Semi-Automatic Ground Environment (SAGE) radar defense system.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Recognizing vulnerabilities in this network, the Air Force sought a system that might survive a nuclear attack to enable a response, thus diminishing the attractiveness of the first strike advantage by enemies (see Mutual assured destruction).
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] In the early 1960s, Baran invented the concept of *distributed adaptive message block switching* in support of the Air Force initiative.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] The concept was first presented to the Air Force in the summer of 1961 as briefing B-265, later published as RAND report P-2626 in 1962, and finally in report RM 3420 in 1964.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] The reports describe a general architecture for a large-scale, distributed, survivable communications network.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] The proposal was composed of three key ideas: use of a decentralized network with multiple paths between any two points; dividing user messages into *message blocks;* and delivery of these messages by store and forward switching.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Baran's network design was focused on high-speed digital communication of voice messages using hardware switches that were low-cost electronics.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Christopher Strachey, who became Oxford University's first Professor of Computation, filed a patent application in the United Kingdom for time-sharing in February 1959.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] In June that year, he gave a paper "Time Sharing in Large Fast Computers" at the UNESCO Information Processing Conference in Paris where he passed the concept on to J.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Licklider (along with John McCarthy) was instrumental in the development of time-sharing.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] After conversations with Licklider about time-sharing with remote computers in 1965, Davies independently invented a similar data communication concept.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] His insight was to use short messages in fixed format with high data transmission rates to achieve rapid communications.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] He went on to develop a design for a hierarchical, high-speed computer network including interface computers and communication protocols.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] He coined the term *packet switching*, and proposed building a commercial nationwide data network in the UK.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] He gave a talk on the proposal in 1966, after which a person from the Ministry of Defence (MoD) told him about Baran's work.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Roger Scantlebury, a member of Davies' team, presented their work (and referenced that of Baran) at the October 1967 Symposium on Operating Systems Principles (SOSP).
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] At the conference, Scantlebury proposed packet switching for use in the ARPANET and persuaded Larry Roberts the economics were favorable to message switching.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Davies had chosen some of the same parameters for his original network design as did Baran, such as a packet size of 1024 bits.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Davies proposed that a local-area network should be built at the laboratory to serve the needs of NPL and prove the feasibility of packet switching.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] After a pilot experiment in early 1969, the NPL Data Communications Network began service in 1970.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Davies was invited to Japan to give a series of lectures on packet switching.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] The NPL team carried out simulation work on datagrams and congestion in networks on a scale to provide data communication across the United Kingdom.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Larry Roberts made the key decisions in the request for proposal to build the ARPANET.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Roberts met Baran in February 1967, but did not discuss networks.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Roberts was known for making decisions quickly.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Immediately after SOSP, he incorporated Davies' concepts and designs for packet switching to enable the data communications on the network, and sought input from Baran.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] A contemporary of Roberts' from MIT, Leonard Kleinrock had researched the application of queueing theory in the field of message switching for his doctoral dissertation in 1961–62 and published it as a book in 1964.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Davies, in his 1966 paper on packet switching, applied Kleinrock's techniques to show that "there is an ample margin between the estimated performance of the [packet-switched] system and the stated requirement" in terms of a satisfactory response time for a human user.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] This addressed a key question about the viability of computer networking.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Larry Roberts brought Kleinrock into the ARPANET project informally in early 1967.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Roberts and Taylor recognized the issue of response time was important, but did not apply Kleinrock's methods to assess this and based their design on a store-and-forward system that was not intended for real-time computing.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] After SOSP, and after Roberts' direction to use packet switching, Kleinrock sought input from Baran and proposed to retain Baran and RAND as advisors.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] The ARPANET working group assigned Kleinrock responsibility to prepare a report on software for the IMP.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] In 1968, Roberts awarded Kleinrock a contract to establish a Network Measurement Center (NMC) at UCLA to measure and model the performance of packet switching in the ARPANET.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Bolt Beranek & Newman (BBN) won the contract to build the network.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Designed principally by Bob Kahn, it was the first wide-area packet-switched network with distributed control.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] The BBN "IMP Guys" independently developed significant aspects of the network's internal operation, including the routing algorithm, flow control, software design, and network control.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] The UCLA NMC and the BBN team also investigated network congestion.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] The Network Working Group, led by Steve Crocker, a graduate student of Kleinrock's at UCLA, developed the host-to-host protocol, the Network Control Program, which was approved by Barry Wessler for ARPA, after he ordered certain more exotic elements to be dropped.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] In 1970, Kleinrock extended his earlier analytic work on message switching to packet switching in the ARPANET.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] The ARPANET was demonstrated at the International Conference on Computer Communication (ICCC) in Washington in October 1972.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] However, fundamental questions about the design of packet-switched networks remained.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Roberts presented the idea of packet switching to communication industry professionals in the early 1970s.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Before ARPANET was operating, they argued that the router buffers would quickly run out.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] After the ARPANET was operating, they argued that packet switching would never be economic without the government subsidy.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Baran had faced the same rejection and thus failed to convince the military to construct a packet switching network in the 1960s.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] The CYCLADES network was designed by Louis Pouzin in the early 1970s to study internetworking.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] It was the first to implement the end-to-end principle of Davies, and make the host computers responsible for the reliable delivery of data on a packet-switched network, rather than this being a service of the network itself.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] His team was thus first to tackle the highly-complex problem of providing user applications with a reliable virtual circuit service while using a best-effort service, an early contribution to what will be the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Bob Metcalfe and others at Xerox PARC outlined the idea of Ethernet and the PARC Universal Packet (PUP) for internetworking.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] In May 1974, Vint Cerf and Bob Kahn described the Transmission Control Program, an internetworking protocol for sharing resources using packet-switching among the nodes.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] The specifications of the TCP were then published in RFC 675 (*Specification of Internet Transmission Control Program*), written by Vint Cerf, Yogen Dalal and Carl Sunshine in December 1974.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] The X.25 protocol, developed by Rémi Després and others, was built on the concept of virtual circuits.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] In the mid-late 1970s and early 1980s, national and international public data networks emerged using X.25 which was developed with participation from France, the UK, Japan, USA and Canada.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] It was complemented with X.75 to enable internetworking.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] In the late 1970s, the monolithic Transmission Control Program was layered as the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), atop the Internet Protocol (IP).
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Many Internet pioneers developed this into the Internet protocol suite and the associated Internet architecture and governance that emerged in the 1980s.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Leonard Kleinrock carried out theoretical work at UCLA during the 1970s analyzing throughput and delay in the ARPANET.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Kleinrock published hundreds of research papers, which ultimately launched a new field of research on the theory and application of queuing theory to computer networks.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] His work on hierarchical routing with student Farouk Kamoun became critical to the operation of the Internet.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Packet switching was shown to be optimal in the Huffman coding sense in 1978.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] For a period in the 1980s and early 1990s, the network engineering community was polarized over the implementation of competing protocol suites, commonly known as the Protocol Wars.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] It was unclear which of the Internet protocol suite and the OSI model would result in the best and most robust computer networks.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor (CMOS) VLSI (very-large-scale integration) technology led to the development of high-speed broadband packet switching during the 1980s–1990s.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] In the 1978 special edition of the Proceedings of the IEEE on packet switching, Bob Kahn, the guest editor, wrote that "analysis has had little direct impact on the network design problem".
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] In Roberts' paper on "Packet Switching Economics" for the L.M.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Ericsson prize for research in data communications in 1982, he referenced only Davies' 1967 paper for SOSP, not the work of Baran or Kleinrock.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Kleinrock's paper for the same prize was titled "Packet Switching Principles".
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] In Roberts' 1986 conference paper on "The ARPANET & Computer Networks", he also cites Baran's 1964 paper and one of his own papers from 1966; but only references Kleinrock's work from the 1970s, which addressed the ARPANET.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] This paper was republished on the web by Roberts in 1995.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] In 1997, along with seven other Internet pioneers, Roberts and Kleinrock co-wrote "Brief History of the Internet" published by the Internet Society.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] In it, Kleinrock is described as having "published the first paper on packet switching theory in July 1961 and the first book on the subject in 1964".
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Many sources about the history of the Internet began to reflect these claims as uncontroversial facts.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] This became the subject of what Katie Hafner called a "paternity dispute" in The New York Times in 2001.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] The disagreement about Kleinrock's contribution to packet switching escalated after a statement made on Kleinrock's profile on the UCLA Computer Science department website sometime in the 1990s.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Here, he was referred to as the "Inventor of the Internet Technology".
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] The webpage's depictions of Kleinrock's achievements provoked anger among some early Internet pioneers.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] The dispute over priority became a public issue after Donald Davies posthumously published a paper in 2001 in which he denied that Kleinrock's work in the early 1960s was related to packet switching, stating "I can find no evidence that he understood the principles of packet switching".
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Davies also described ARPANET project manager Larry Roberts as supporting Kleinrock, referring to Roberts' writings online and Kleinrock's UCLA webpage profile as "very misleading".
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Walter Isaacson wrote that Kleinrock's claims "led to an outcry among many of the other Internet pioneers, who publicly attacked Kleinrock and said that his brief mention of breaking messages into smaller pieces did not come close to being a proposal for packet switching".
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Davies' paper reignited a previous dispute over who deserves credit for getting the ARPANET online between engineers at Bolt, Beranek, and Newman (BBN) who had been involved in building and designing the ARPANET IMP on the one side, and ARPA-related researchers on the other.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] This earlier dispute is exemplified by BBN's Will Crowther, who in a 1990 oral history described Paul Baran's packet switching design (which he called hot-potato routing), as "crazy" and non-sensical, despite the ARPA team having advocated for it.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Former IPTO director Bob Taylor also joined the debate, stating that "authors who have interviewed dozens of Arpanet pioneers know very well that the Kleinrock-Roberts claims are not believed".
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Walter Isaacson notes that "until the mid-1990s Kleinrock had credited [Baran and Davies] with coming up with the idea of packet switching".
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] A subsequent version of Kleinrock's biography webpage was copyrighted in 2009 by Kleinrock.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] He was called on to defend his position over subsequent decades.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] A paper published in the journal *Internet Histories* in 2019 supported Kleinrock's view; the author interviewed Kleinrock and Roberts, and did not interview Scantlebury.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] In 2023, Kleinrock acknowledged that his work published in the early 1960s was about message switching and claimed he was thinking about packet switching.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Primary sources and historians recognize Baran and Davies for independently inventing the concept of digital packet switching used in modern computer networking including the ARPANET and the Internet.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Kleinrock has received many awards for his ground-breaking applied mathematical research on packet switching, carried out in the 1970s, which was an extension of his pioneering work in the early 1960s on the optimization of message delays in communication networks.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Russell said "'Internet history' also suffers from a ... methodological, problem: it tends to be too close to its sources.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Many Internet pioneers are alive, active, and eager to shape the histories that describe their accomplishments.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Many museums and historians are equally eager to interview the pioneers and to publicize their stories".
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Packet switching may be classified into connectionless packet switching, using datagrams, and connection-oriented packet switching, using virtual circuits.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Examples of connectionless systems are Ethernet, IP, and the User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Connection-oriented systems include X.25, Frame Relay, Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS), and TCP.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] In connectionless mode, each packet is labeled with a destination address, source address, and port numbers.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] It may also be labeled with the sequence number of the packet.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] This information eliminates the need for a pre-established path to help the packet find its way to its destination, but means that more information is needed in the packet header, which is therefore larger.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] The packets are routed individually, sometimes taking different paths, resulting in out-of-order delivery.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] At the destination, the original message may be reassembled in the correct order, based on the packet sequence numbers.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Thus, a virtual circuit carrying a byte stream is provided to the application by a transport layer protocol, although the network only provides a connectionless network layer service.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Connection-oriented transmission requires a setup phase to establish the parameters of communication before any packet is transferred.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] The signaling protocols used for setup allow the application to specify its requirements and discover link parameters.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Acceptable values for service parameters may be negotiated.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] The packets transferred may include a connection identifier rather than address information and the packet header can be smaller, as it only needs to contain this code and any information, such as length, timestamp, or sequence number, which is different for different packets.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] In this case, address information is only transferred to each node during the connection setup phase, when the route to the destination is discovered and an entry is added to the switching table in each network node through which the connection passes.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] When a connection identifier is used, routing a packet requires the node to look up the connection identifier in a table.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Connection-oriented transport layer protocols such as TCP provide a connection-oriented service by using an underlying connectionless network.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] In this case, the end-to-end principle dictates that the end nodes, not the network itself, are responsible for the connection-oriented behavior.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] In telecommunication networks, packet switching is used to optimize the usage of channel capacity and increase robustness.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Compared to circuit switching, packet switching is highly dynamic, allocating channel capacity based on usage instead of explicit reservations.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] This can reduce wasted capacity caused by underutilized reservations at the cost of removing bandwidth guarantees.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] In practice, congestion control is generally used in IP networks to dynamically negotiate capacity between connections.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Packet switching may also increase the robustness of networks in the face of failures.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] If a node fails, connections do not need to be interrupted, as packets may be routed around the failure.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Packet switching is used in the Internet and most local area networks.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] The Internet is implemented by the Internet Protocol Suite using a variety of link layer technologies.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] For example, Ethernet and Frame Relay are common.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Newer mobile phone technologies (e.g., GSM, LTE) also use packet switching.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Packet switching is associated with connectionless networking because, in these systems, no connection agreement needs to be established between communicating parties prior to exchanging data.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] X.25, the international CCITT standard of 1976, is a notable use of packet switching in that it provides to users a service of flow-controlled virtual circuits.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] These virtual circuits reliably carry variable-length packets with data order preservation.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] DATAPAC in Canada was the first public network to support X.25, followed by TRANSPAC in France.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) is another virtual circuit technology.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] It differs from X.25 in that it uses small fixed-length packets (cells), and that the network imposes no flow control to users.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Technologies such as MPLS and the Resource Reservation Protocol (RSVP) create virtual circuits on top of datagram networks.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] MPLS and its predecessors, as well as ATM, have been called "fast packet" technologies.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] MPLS, indeed, has been called "ATM without cells".
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] Virtual circuits are especially useful in building robust failover mechanisms and allocating bandwidth for delay-sensitive applications.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] The work of Donald Davies in the late 1960s on data communication and computer network design became well known in the United States, Europe and Japan.
[src:dpdk-networking/packet-switching] This was the "cornerstone" that inspired numerous packet switching networks in the decade following.
[src:dpdk-networking/smartnic] A **data processing unit** (**DPU**) is a programmable computer processor that tightly integrates a general-purpose CPU with network interface hardware.
[src:dpdk-networking/smartnic] They are also occasionally called "**IPUs**" (infrastructure processing unit) or "**SmartNICs**".
[src:dpdk-networking/smartnic] These devices can be attractive to cloud computing providers whose servers might otherwise spend a significant amount of CPU time on these tasks, cutting into the cycles they can provide to guests.
[src:dpdk-networking/smartnic] They see use in other kinds of data center environments as well due to their improved power consumption efficiency for routine networking tasks compared to general-purpose CPUs.
